  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Meher seed provision for drought affected populations of SNNP Oromia Tigray and Amhara Region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The 2015 El Ni&#xF1;o episode has had a major impact on the agriculture sector performance with two consecutive crop failures and crop production having decreased by 50/90%. Access to seed continues to be a major problem in particular for the most vulnerable members of the community. The two main planting seasons in Ethiopia are the Belg and the Meher. According to OCHA&#x2019;s February Humanitarian Bulletin, only 30% of households have been assisted with seeds for the Belg planting season. The next planting season is the Meher which accounts for more than 80% of the crop production in the country. Should this planting season also be missed due to lack of seeds the consequences will prove disastrous.

Considering this, the community leaders and the regional authorities are demanding external assistance for seed provision to save the life and protect livelihoods of the people. It is crucial to address the seed shortage problem in order to allow the farmers to recover from the two consecutive crop failures and avoid further depletion of the assets as a coping mechanism by the most vulnerable members of the community. A serious deterioration of the situation, including risk of extreme food insecurity, cannot be excluded if farmers fail to take advantage of the forthcoming Meher production.

Through this action GOAL aims to support a total of 31,500 households 

- Oromia Region: Siraro, West Arsi Zone 
- Tigray Region: Afherom, Central Zone: Hawzen, Eastern Zone
- Amhara Region: Beheret, North Showa Zone Borena, Oromia Zone Sayint, Dawe Harewa, South Wollo Zone


The seeds being provided have been selected by the Woreda Agricultural office and the request was sent to the GOAL office in the form of a letter. The seeds requested for this action are Barley 46.9Mt, Chickpea 93.8MT Haricot Bean 180MT Sorghum 41.3MT Teff 146.3 MT and Wheat 293.8T</narrative>
  </description>
